:: DrifterStory2 [en] {"position":"2900,675","size":"100,100"}
Just as Mabel’s cold, mechanical claws were about to tear through my throat, a force slammed into me, knocking me aside. It was the drifter. He stood before me, his mind fractured, his eyes wild with a desperate, frantic light.

'My wife... she was... just like this...' he whimpered, before erupting into a defiant scream. 'NOT THEM! NOT AGAIN!'

Mabel tilted her head, a sickening metallic screech emanating from her throat. 'Such a pity. Why are you so afraid of me?'

The sound of tearing flesh filled the room. With his final breath, the man lunged forward, grabbing my sleeve. 'My wife... parking lot... circus back door... keys... in the office...'

His eyes went dull. He had bought us a few minutes of life with his own.

[[Find Mark's letter->Mark's letter in the office]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Ending 1 [en] {"position":"3575,500","size":"100,100"}
//The Grand Finale: Ending 1//

I held onto the evidence I had gathered within the park. Once released, the news shook the entire nation.

The SCP Foundation acted with clinical efficiency, swiftly placing the park under total lockdown. From that day forward, it became a "Red Zone"—a forbidden land strictly regulated and contained by the Foundation's iron grip.

Yet, in the digital world outside, the cycle of cyber-harassment and systemic injustice continued unabated.

I can still vividly recall every horror I witnessed that day. I can still see the faces of those who were transformed into bloodthirsty, frenzied monsters by the park’s twisted logic. Above all, I carry the weight of my own guilt.

As a media creator who understands the dark mechanics of the internet, I refuse to stand by and watch more victims fall to the "tyranny of the masses." I have decided to use my influence to stand firmly with those who are being unfairly scrutinized by the public eye.

I don't know how many lives I can truly change, but I know one thing: this is the only way to prevent more tragedies like "The Park" from ever happening again.
(display:"Styles")


:: Ending 2 [en] {"position":"3575,650","size":"100,100"}
//The Grand Finale: Ending 2//

The world remains infested with cyber-harassment and countless injustices, yet you still refuse to lend a helping hand. You remain paralyzed, still feeling that suffocating shame of being the "outlier" or the "minority" in the face of the roaring crowd.

You have become a shadow within the masses—a symbol of the total loss of self.

Despite having witnessed the literal manifestation of malice in that park, you chose the safety of silence over the danger of the truth. The park didn't just trap your body; it successfully harvested your soul. You are now just another cog in the machine that creates monsters.
(display:"Styles")


:: Enter the left door [en] {"position":"2225,675","size":"100,100"}
We stepped cautiously into the room, only to realize the deafening, rhythmic noise fading into the distance. The scenery shifted; the room turned into a twisting, turning labyrinth.

Astor:
"Oh no!"

We spun around to block the door before it closed, yet it had already slammed and shut behind us. We are trapped within the maze, having no choice but to follow the fading echoes hoping to seek for an exit. As we wandered, the path grew more confusing, a sense of hopelessness took hold. A thick white mist began to swirl around us, growing denser by  seconds. Lost in the haze of fear and confusion, we all slowly suffocated by the fog, drawing our final breaths in the dark.

[[Go back->Page 16]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Enter the right door [en] {"position":"2225,800","size":"100,100"}
Recalling all the signboards we had seen along the way, we cautiously opened the right door. Inside was vast and hollow, leaving a single table in this huge room.

There is a piece of paper lying on top of the desk, a paper that notes down the hidden key to the entire mystery of this secret chamber.

---

The Revelation

He never belonged here, not even as a child.

While other children were havinfg fun and gathered in packs, he would be curled up in a corner, immersed in the stories woven within his own mind. He loved to fantasize; he loved his solitude. He wasn't slow, and he wasn't "weird"—he simply refused to follow the trivial rules of this world. 

Yet all his behaviours were viewed as sickness by the adults.

His parents never tried to truly understand him. They dragged him to countless hospitals and made him do endless examinations. At home, they forced him to be "normal." They forced him to speak, to fit in, to smile, and to appease everyone around him. The more he resisted, the deeper their disappointment grew. His parents never truly understand him, 

("Why are you such a failure?" 
"Why is everyone else normal except for you?")

He could never feel love from his family.

In school, he couldn't blend in; he was a perpetual loner. He was branded with labels: *freak, weirdo, idiot.*

However, his silence only caused him hatred. The teachers would ignore him, dismissing him as a "troubled student." When he got bullied, He would even get blamed on by the teachers *"Why do they only pick on you and no one else? have you ever considered that you were actually the problem?."*

He had done nothing wrong. He had harmed no one. He only wanted to live in his own world. Yet he was told to discard all those "unrealistic fantasies."

No one ever cared what he loved. No one tried to step into his heart. No one ever told him (being different is okay.)

Bit by bit, his spirit was corroded. He began to fear crowds, noise, avoidied to communicate with others. He locked himself away in a bottomless labyrinth—a maze where he was entirely alone, a maze that he could never find the exit.

And so, the quiet child who loved to dream became the monster trapped in this maze, weaving illusions of his own.

---

I noticed another letter on the table; the handwriting matched Mark’s perfectly.

"I think I finally understand why the staffs killed all the vistors who breached the rules. Perhaps the boy in the story is the host? He was always shackled by rules, he hated the and had to give us a taste of what he felt. They crave to punish those who created the rules..."

As I read this, I remember reading similar news reports, bully cases like this happens too frequently and people are all ignoring them. A heavy, hollow feeling overwhelmed my chest.

Astor: "What do we do now?"

Clara: "Let’s see if we can leave here first."
[[Next ->DrifterStory]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Exit via the Staff Passage [en] {"position":"2475,375","size":"100,100"}
We sprinted through the staff passage, our lungs burning, driven by the pure terror of the mascot behind us. But as we burst through the exit into the open air, the realization hit me like a physical blow: it was a setup.

That staff member—the one who had "helped" us—was standing right there. He wasn't running. He wasn't hiding. He was waiting.

Before I could even scream, his hands were upon us. With a swift, mechanical brutality, he seized our throats. There was a sharp, splintering CRACK as he snapped our necks like dry twigs.

The last thing I felt was a surge of white-hot agony. Then, the park, the rules, and the screams all vanished into an eternal, silent dark.
(display:"Styles")


