:: Head for the Maze to hide [en] {"position":"1725,500","size":"100,100"}
We trudged all the way to the entrance of the maze. After making sure it was safe inside, we slipped into a corner and hid— I remembered the rules: (out there is not safe right now.)

Samuel: “Fuck! What the hell is going on out there? And what’s with these stupid fucking rules?”

Me: “I don’t know… but one thing’s for sure—this is no ordinary place. The only thing I do know is this: if we break their rules, we’ll see each other in hell, just like we promised.”

Samuel: “Spit it out! Are you trying to get us killed talking like that?”

Me: “Weren’t we already asking for death the moment we stepped in here?”

Samuel: “Uh… come to think of it, why are there even these rules? It’s so strange.”

He asked the very question that had been burning at the back of my mind.

*Who are “they,” really?*

I gazed across our surroundings. The maze wasn’t just a tangle of branching paths—it was filled with small rooms in between. I remembered I read reviews on this maze. Visitors are told to use hints hidden in these rooms to navigate a story, piecing clues together to find the exit. It was similar with the 'escape rooms' trending these days.  drawing and attracting crowds of curious players.

However, the maze in front of me had something off from all those visitor reviews.

The maze was cloaked in a strange, thin mist fog that blurs all the path ahead. Making us pretty much impossible to see where the corridor ended.

Samuel got curious and told me to go find the source of the weird noise. He grabbed my arm tightly and dragged me to a forked way where two rooms were in front of us.
Then he stopped. Turned to me.

“Where do *you* think that sound is coming from?”

[[The room with faint traces of blood at the threshold]]
[[The room with a doorway that looked unnervingly clean]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Head for the Park Exit [en] {"position":"1725,350","size":"100,100"}
We stumbled breathlessly towards the amusement park’s exit, only to find the iron gates closeed.
“Damn it! Why did they close so early today?” Samuel roared, slamming his fist against the cold metal. 

A chill ran down my spine. I remembered the rigid rules, the ones no one ever questioned. The blackout in the circus was around 10:30. It had only been a couple of minutes after the show ended. The park was supposed to close at 11:30. Someone had closed the gates an hour early. 

“What the hell is happening? What even are those things?” I whispered, my voice trembling.

Samuel lost all hope in his eyes. “So this is the anomaly you warned me about? Thats some crazy horror. No wonder there were rumors about people keep coming back, its a one way park afterall.”

“Nah, Theres no way,” I shot back, scanning the chaos around us. “If this ever hit the internet, no one would dare set foot here again.”

The scene was a nightmare. Tourists scattered in every direction, their screams attracted the bloodthirsty creatures, prowling the grounds, hunting with relentless fury.

Everyone had broken the rules. They had nothing that they could do except from accepting the fate of the monsters killing them.

“What do we do?” Samuel’s voice cracked,he had finally lost it. Fear finally broke through his bravado shattering his last bit of hope.

I swallowed hard, forcing calm into my words. “It’s too dangerous here. Let’s move to a nearby zone. Staying out in the open is same as suicide.”

[[Next-> Heading towards the dark forest area]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Hide in a room within the Staff Passage [en] {"position":"2475,500","size":"100,100"}
My instinct warned me that the exit might be another trap, so we dove deeper into the passage, searching for any possible cover. Just as the thundering steps of Mabel were about to reach us, a door swung open and a pair of hands yanked us inside.

"Are you guys okay?" a girl whispered.

"I'm Astor," one said. "And I'm Clara," the other added.

We exchanged hurried introductions in the dim light. Samuel collapsed against the wall, clutching his chest. "Yeah... thank God you saved us," he panted. Then, his voice rose in pitch, his eyes darting around frantically. "Do you have any idea what’s going on? Why are we here? This whole thing... it’s driving me crazy!"

The pressure of losing everything was finally breaking him.

Astor looked at us with a heavy expression. "We don't know why we were brought to this world either. But," she paused, pulling something from her jacket, "we just discovered this..."

[[Next -> Page 21]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Immediately scramble back a few steps [en] {"position":"1600,400","size":"100,100"}
"What the hell are you doing? We have to go!" Samuel barked, lunging forward to grab my arm. He pulled me into a dead sprint toward the exit. Behind us, the staff members stopped their pursuit, watching us with those twisted, frozen expressions.

I tripped and hit the ground hard near the gate.
"Holy sh*t, you scared the crap out of me!" Samuel gasped, breathless. "What the hell is going on?"

I didn't answer. My eyes were fixed on the brochure I’d dropped. The ink had changed. The once-boring safety tips were gone, replaced by words written in a violent, bleeding crimson.
0. The park closes at 10:30 PM. Everyone except staff must vacate the premises. If you fail to leave before the gates close, seek a safe location immediately. Do not move until you are certain the danger has passed.
0. After hours, patrol staff will check equipment every three hours. You may seek help from them if necessary.
0. There are two types of staff: those in dark blue uniforms are trustworthy. Those in red uniforms are senior regulators. Do not let them find you. If they catch you after hours, you will receive the "worst possible treatment."
0. If you hear strange noises behind you, do not turn around. It is Mabel, the park mascot. Do not look at her; making eye contact is extremely dangerous.
0. If you experience hallucinations or auditory delusions, stay away from the source or close your eyes for one minute until they pass.
0. Avoid strong light sources. Approaching them will result in unbearable pain and misfortune.

"More rules..." I muttered. I knew this place was off, but I never expected a massacre.

Samuel looked over my shoulder, his face turning pale. "What kind of sick joke is this? 'Worst possible treatment'?"

I scanned our surroundings. In the distance, a group of those red-uniformed silhouettes was drifting toward us. I checked the map in the brochure. "We aren't safe here. We need to move, now!"

What will you do?
[[Head for the Park Exit]]
[[Head for the Maze to hide]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Mark's letter in the office [en] {"position":"3200,550","size":"100,100"}
//Found Mark's letter//

The Incident:
A student who had just finished her college entrance exams dyed her hair a vibrant color and got a tattoo to celebrate the end of years of grueling study. Her family took her on a trip to celebrate. But after posting photos on social media, she became the target of a vicious cyber-harassment campaign. Netizens attacked her character, accusing her of being "indecent" and violating the conservative modesty expected of a student. They claimed she was only trying to "attract male attention." Unable to withstand the cruelty of this relentless online violence, the girl ultimately ended her life by jumping into a river.

The Park is located right near that site.

The Entity Representing This Trauma: The Giant Mascot of the Park.

The Confession:
As a member of the media, I witnessed this tragedy unfold. I felt a deep sympathy for her, but in the end, I remained silent. I was paralyzed by the fear of being targeted by the same mob.

The Revelation from Mark:
Mark realized that the rules were designed as a trap to benefit "Them." The rules are not just there to make you suffer the consequences of disobedience; they are a psychological engine designed to lead you, step by step, into a dead end—leaving you defenseless and ready for slaughter.

[[Find the key]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Page 15 [en] {"position":"1975,700","size":"100,100"}
I had no choice but to follow them. There are endless corridors after walking out of the room, twisting like a labyrinth without end.

Along the way, we notice strange markings etched into the walls. We had no idea when they were placed there. We followed the signs bringing us into another chamber.

This room is different—cleaner, stripped of clutter, its emptiness unsettling in its order.

“Look,” Samuel whispers, pointing. “There’s something here… like a letter.”

On the paper, scrawled in a hurried hand, are words that chill the blood:

I have never seen so many powerful creatures, especially the illusion itself—it trapped me and other visitors in this world ruled by its twisted rules. They are obsessed with obedience, slaughtering anyone who dares to defy them. I don’t know their true motives, but they seem to sense that my presence threatens their plan. These monsters are beyond the level we could handle. It will take many of us to fight them. I must gather all the data and send it back before moreof us are killed by these monsters.

First, I have to survive. This maze belongs to part of the illusion. One wrong step, one careless choiceis going to bring me death in confusion and despair. I have marked all the paths I’ve taken to avoid its traps and monsters. If anyone who see this get lost, please follow my signs.

— Mark Davis, former SCP staff

I whisper, “When was this written?” 

No one responded, it was clearly that no one had a single clue if its legit.

Yet we have no choice now but to follow Mark’s trail, hoping that his path might lead us out alive.

[[Next ->Page 16]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Page 16 [en] {"position":"2100,725","size":"100,100"}
We follow Mark’s trail, his markings guide us through the endless maze.  Signs hang above each paths filled with illusions.
“This is the right way.” “Everyone goes this way.” “You’ll regret not choosing this.” “This is the normal path. Illusionized words and phrases are filled all over the road.

Yet Mark’s hints never fails us. There are traps illusion to lure the unwary, Mark's hints dodges all the traps and danger.

As we arricved the exit of the maze, there was one final set of doors left for us to choose, Mark's markings vanished, leaving us stranded at the doors of decisions. Two doors stand side by side, squeaky and creepy noise lies between the door.

Marching feets and a hollow echo of applausecame from the left door.

Sigh of wind comes from the right door, broken whispers rise and fall like fragments of forgotten prayers.

The air thickens, pressing against our skin. The maze demands a choice.

We must decide:

[[Enter the left door]]
[[Enter the right door]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Page 18 [en] {"position":"2225,300","size":"100,100"}
He led us back to the main thoroughfare of the park. My breath hitched in my throat—what I saw was impossible. The street that had been a slaughterhouse moments ago, littered with bodies and soaked in crimson, was now unnaturally clean. It was as if the chaos had been erased from existence.

"What... what happened?" Samuel stammered, his eyes bulging. He rubbed them vigorously, convinced he was hallucinating. "There was blood everywhere... how is it all gone?"

I was just as paralyzed by shock. I knelt and touched the ground; it was dry, pristine, without a single trace of the carnage we had witnessed. I looked up at the staff member in the dark blue uniform.

"Is this it?" I whispered.

He offered an unfathomable smile, one that sent a chill down my spine. "This is as much help as I can provide," he replied.

To my surprise, Samuel actually muttered a "thank you" to him. Without a word of farewell, the man turned and strode away, merging back into the darkness.

{(if: $isAskingAboutFriend) 
[[[Next->Page 19A]]]
(else:)
[[[Next->Page 19B]]]
(display:"Styles")}


:: Page 19A [en] {"position":"2350,250","size":"100,100"}
I was still dissecting the staff member's behavior in my mind when I decided to steal one last look at his retreating figure. My blood turned to ice. His uniform—the one that was supposed to be a safe, reliable blue—had bled into a sickeningly vivid crimson.

"Samuel, don't—"

Before I could finish my warning, a piercing scream ripped through the air, only to be cut short by a sudden, suffocating silence.

Then, I heard it. From the darkness directly behind me came a sound that defied logic: a woman’s desperate weeping, layered with the erratic, metallic crackle of an electrical short circuit.

I couldn't move. I didn't want to know what was back there. Was my mind finally snapping? Was it a hallucination, or was it Her... that nightmare in the shape of a mascot?

<!--According to Rule 4: Do not turn around. Do not acknowledge it.-->

At this moment, you should:
[[Do not look back, run for your life immediately]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Page 19B [en] {"position":"2350,375","size":"100,100"}
I froze as I realized the staff member’s uniform had bled from a safe blue into a glaring, hostile scarlet.

Samuel lost it. A sharp, jagged scream escaped his throat before I could cover his mouth. It was the one sound we couldn't afford to make.

The sound acted like a beacon. The giant mascot, Mabel, snapped her head toward us. The moment her dead, glass eyes locked onto our horrified faces, she began to charge. Her movements were a sickening mix of mechanical stutters and predatory speed.

There was no time for a plan. There was only the primal urge to survive.

Where will you go?
[[Exit via the Staff Passage]]
[[Hide in a room within the Staff Passage]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Page 22A [en] {"position":"2775,325","size":"100,100"}
"What does that even mean?" I asked, my voice trembling with rising anger. "If they hate the system, why take it out on us? Why drag innocent people into this nightmare?"

My heart sank as the silence stretched. "Are you saying... there’s no way out?"

Astor stared at the SCP badge in his hand, his brow furrowed. "Not necessarily," he said after a long pause. "I have a friend—a VIP regular. We spent a lot of time here before... before all this. He once mentioned a hidden service tunnel inside 'Colorful World' that leads directly beyond the park perimeter."

He looked up, his eyes flashing with a renewed sense of purpose.

"It’s our only shot. Let’s move."

[[Next->Page 23]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Page 22B {"position":"2775,450","size":"100,100"}
Samuel’s eyes were bloodshot, his voice cracking as he yelled, "What does that even mean? If they hate the world, why take it out on us? Why drag innocent people into their nightmare?"

Astor stepped forward, his voice calm but heavy. "I know it’s unfair, Samuel. But anger won't get us through the night."

I looked at them both, my heart sinking. "So... is that it? Are we trapped here forever?"

Astor paused, staring at the SCP badge in his hand as if searching for an answer. After a long silence, he looked up. "Maybe not. I have a friend—a VIP regular. We spent a lot of time here before the 'change.' He once mentioned a service tunnel deep within 'Colorful World' that leads straight beyond the park perimeter."

He tightened the straps on his bag, his eyes flashing with a renewed sense of purpose.

"Let’s move."
[[Next->DrifterStory]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Page 23 [en] {"position":"2900,325","size":"100,100"}
But when I finally reached him, something was horribly wrong. Samuel’s eyes were hollow, devoid of any spark of life. His face was as pale as parchment, and his clothes hung in bloody rags. He moved with a sickening rigidity, like a puppet jerked by invisible strings. He didn't respond to my voice; he didn't even blink. Instead, his lips were curled into a faint, grotesque smile—the exact same icy, unsettling grin worn by the monsters in the red uniforms.

'Watch out! Don't go near him! He’s not Samuel anymore!' Astor’s voice cut through the air, sharp and desperate. He lunged forward, grabbing my shoulder to pull me back. 'They’ve taken him! He’s one of them now!'

I snapped back to my senses and tried to retreat, but 'Samuel' was faster. His hand—cold as a corpse—clamped around my throat with staggering strength, as if he intended to crush my windpipe. At that heart-stopping moment, a familiar figure charged between us: it was the drifter from the corridor.

He stood as a shield before me, his mind clearly fractured beyond repair.

'My wife... they did this to her too...' he whimpered, before his voice broke into a defiant roar. 'NOT AGAIN!'

Mabel’s voice echoed, dripping with mockery: 'What a shame. Why are you two so afraid of me?'

After the drifter was brutally mauled, he gasped out his final words with his dying breath: 'My wife... parking lot... circus back door... keys... office...'

[[Find Mark's letter->Mark's letter in the office]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Pretend everything is fine [en Scene1.7] {"position":"975,350","size":"100,100"}
"I’m fine," I replied quickly, trying to steady my voice. Was I really that rattled by the drifter earlier? "Maybe I’m just feeling a bit under the weather today."

Samuel gave a noncommittal grunt. He didn’t press any further, his attention already drifting back to the crimson tent.

[[Next->page 8]]
(display:"Styles")

<!--Ending‑1: Murder True -->


:: Response [en Scene1.3] {"position":"475,250","size":"100,100"}
I gave my wrists a hard tug. Seeing I couldn't break free, I sighed and looked down at him. "Get up first. What exactly did you mean by... they?"

The homeless man stammered, his eyes wide with terror, |shake>["Those rules... they're real... Don't break them... Don't... "] With that, he spun around and bolted.

[[Next->page 4]]
(display:"Styles")


