:: Survival [en] {"position":"2900,800","size":"100,100"}
We scrambled into the cramped office, slamming the door just as Mabel’s heavy stabs at the wood began. In the dim light of a flickering monitor, I found a crumpled envelope on the desk. It was a letter from Mark, one of the lead designers.

As I read, a cold realization washed over me.

"Samuel, Astor... look at this," I whispered, my voice trembling. "The rules... they aren't meant to save us. Mark discovered the truth before he 'disappeared.' The monsters didn't just want us to suffer for breaking the rules; they wanted to condition us. Each rule is a psychological hook, designed to lead us step-by-step into a dead end where we can no longer fight back."

The 'Safe' Blue Uniforms, the 'Exit' signs, the 'Don't Look Back' command—it was all a setup to make our movements predictable. They profit from our blind obedience.

"To escape," I said, looking at the door being battered from the outside, "we have to stop thinking like victims. We have to find the flaws in their logic."

[[Found Mark's letter->Mark's letter in the office]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Tell him about the strange atmosphere [en Scene1.7] {"position":"975,225","size":"100,100"}
“I don’t know… don’t you feel something’s off here?” I whispered, glancing around.

"Where?" Samuel asked, unbothered.

“The whole atmosphere,” I said. “Did you notice the staff at the park gates?”

"Them?" Samuel chuckled. "What’s wrong with them? Other than the fact that they looked completely miserable while sprouting all that 'magical' nonsense? Honestly, they looked exactly like me when I'm clocked in at the office. Haha!"

I didn't push the subject further. Maybe I was just being paranoid.

[[Next->page 8]]
(display:"Styles")

<!--Ending +0 -->


:: The Visitor Service Hub [en] {"position":"1975,300","size":"100,100"}
Following Samuel, I crept forward, my heart hammering against my ribs. We peeked into the Service Hub; it was hollow and silent. But just as we stepped over the threshold, a voice materialized from the shadows right next to us.

"What exactly are you doing here?"

That twisted, inhuman face loomed in the dim light. "AAAAAAAH! RUN!" Samuel didn't hesitate; he grabbed me and lunged back into the night.

But I skidded to a halt, my eyes locked on the figure. "Wait!" I hissed.

This staff member wasn't like the other. He was dressed in a crisp, dark blue uniform—immaculate and professional. There was no blood, no jagged claws. He looked like a beacon of order in this chaotic nightmare.

According to the rules, the blue-uniformed staff were trustworthy.

Samuel seemed to realize this too, his frantic pace slowing to a stop. I took a tentative step toward the man, my breath hitching.

Should we ask him for the way out?
(link: "Ask")
[(set: $isAskingAboutFriend to true)(go-to: "Ask")]
(link: "Don't ask")
[(set: $isAskingAboutFriend to false)(go-to: "Don't ask")]
(display:"Styles")


:: The room with a doorway that looked unnervingly clean [en] {"position":"1850,525","size":"100,100"}
I trembled behind Samuel, waiting for the door to swing open.

There was nothing inside. Just an empty room. I felt relax, until I felt something; a cold mist seeping up from the floor, slowly coiling around my ankles. Then it hit me.

*The rules.* That's the monster's hallucination— exactly what they'd warned us about.

"Close your eyes right now!" I shouted. 

Before we could even react, the mist had already risen to our necks. The thick, suffocating mist crawled into our lungs, I could feel it reaching every single bone of my body, freezing every organ and cell to death. 

Neither of us made it.

As my conciousness faded gradually, I took my one last breath.

**Cause of death: Hunted by the first kind of monsters —The Illusion.**

{[[Go back ->Head for the Maze to hide]]
(display:"Styles")}


:: The room with faint traces of blood at the threshold [en] {"position":"1850,675","size":"100,100"}
The bloodstains at the doorway brought me an unease I couldn't shake. I stood behind Samuel as he pushed the door open.

As he opened the door, i see two guys, two guys who were both drenched in blood. They flinched at the sight of us, just as startled as we were.

We greeted them carefully as if wewere scared if they were one of those monsters or impostors of the park.

*"Hello. My name's Astor."*
*"I am Clara."*

The moment we stepped inside,(the door shut behind us with a loud bang). It is one of the maze's cruel tricks—once one has chosen his own paths, there will be no turning back for him. Every step is a gamble.

I lowered my voice. "Do you two know what's happening?"

Clara shook her head. "We have no idea."

Astor added, "We saw those… *things*… and ran straight here. Everything was fine just a few days ago and now there are monsters and crazy shit i never thought that actually exist."

I pressed further. "Have you been here before?"

Astor nodded. "A friend of mine is a VIP member of this group. He used to bring me and a group of friends here all the time. It was just few days ago, Clara and I brought our parents here. They said they were coming too… but then we couldnt even contact them, they just vanished like that.'

My mind got flooded with so many questions—so many question marks in my mind that I barely knew where to start. Before I could kept on asking, Samuel cut in.

"Look!" He pointed. "What the hell is that big red arrow?"

Astor frowned. "That's strange… we have never seen that before."

Samuel's eyes lit up with certainty. "Let's follow it."

Clara's agreed without doubting anything. "The exit from here leads straight to the park gate. If we go this way… maybe we can actually get out of here."

[[Next ->Page 15]]
(display:"Styles")


:: Unlock back door [en] {"position":"3450,550","size":"100,100"}
The path to the parking lot was more desolate than we imagined. The streetlamps flickered like dying pulses, stretching our shadows into grotesque shapes that seemed to chase us. The sickly sweet scent of the park had faded, replaced by the sharp tang of motor oil and a faint, metallic smell of fresh blood.

Just as we neared the entrance, a piercing screech tore through the silence. From the gloom, dozens of twisted figures emerged—red-uniformed monsters and hollow-eyed puppets like Samuel, standing shoulder to shoulder to form an impenetrable wall of flesh and machinery.

'How did they know?' Luna whispered, her voice trembling. I gripped the five keys in my hand, remembering Mark’s warning about 'hallucinatory manipulation.' The entities knew our plan. They were using the rules to cage us.

'It’s an illusion!' Astor hissed, brandishing a broken table leg. 'The entities are controlling them. We have to break through!'

We charged. Astor fought like a man possessed, fending off the reaching claws while Luna and I sprinted into the depths of the parking lot. We reached a fork where three tunnels diverged, each bathed in a different light.

The First Tunnel: Littered with red uniforms, echoing with the hum of heavy machinery.

The Second Tunnel: A weathered Mabel doll sat at the entrance under a soft, inviting glow—yet it felt like a predator's trap.

The Third Tunnel: Simple and unadorned, with a single beam of steady, natural light shining from the far end.

Luna was frantic. 'Which one? If we choose wrong, we’re dead!'

Astor recalled Rule 6: 'Stay away from bright lights; they will bring you agony.' But I looked at the steady beam in the third tunnel. Mark’s letter flashed in my mind: The rules are the trap. The truth lies in the gaps.

'The "Rule" wants us to stay in the dark,' I gritted my teeth, pointing to the third tunnel. 'That light... that's the only place the illusion can't reach. Follow me!'

The roars behind us grew deafening as the monsters broke through Astor’s defense, closing in step by step. Their silhouettes twisted and contorted in the dim light, sending a bone-chilling shiver down my spine. 'There’s no time to hesitate!' I gritted my teeth, running firmly at the third tunnel.

{(if: $sanity > 20)[[[Next->Ending 1]]]
(elseif: $sanity < 10)[[[Next->Ending 2]]]
(display:"Styles")}


:: page 1 [en Scene1] {"position":"225,300","size":"100,100"}
As dusk approached, I entered the park and walked through a long corridor adorned with flags depicting the park’s characters, accompanied by an upbeat yet oddly distorted tune—rather peculiar. 

Beside the corridor was a vast parking lot, darkened for some reason, leaving only a faint beam of light in the distance, adding an eerie ambiance to the bustling park. I hurried past that unsettling area.
 
{[[Next->page 2]]
(display:"Styles")}


:: page 10 [en Scene2.2] {"position":"1350,300","size":"100,100"}
{|highlight>[BOOM! ](set: $sanity to it - 8)
<br>
All in a sudden, the lights snapped off.
<br>
No warning, no flicker, just sudden, absolute darkness, as though someone ripped the plug from the wall, plunging the entire venue into an abyss.
<br>
A crowd of nearly five hundred was left reeling in the dark. The air filled with the sharp wails of terrified children, the muffled curses of adults, and the chaotic scuffling of those trying to flee.
<br>
Ten minutes of suffocating darkness passed.
<br>
Then, a voice crackled through the silence. Cold. Precise.
<br>
The Host: "Let the show... BEGIN!"
<br>
[[Next->page 11]]
(display:"Styles")}


:: page 11 [en Scene2.3] {"position":"1475,300","size":"100,100"}
A blood-curdling shriek ripped through the darkness. In the dim light, I saw a staff member in a red uniform—his hand, now a jagged claw, had gutted a man holding a professional camera. Fresh blood began to seep from the jagged wound. The staffer’s face was a twisted, contorted mask of flesh, utterly inhuman.

Panic erupted. Some tried to call for help, only to find the lines dead. Others, driven by a morbid, stunned reflex, actually held up their phones to record. As more rules were broken, more of these "alternates" emerged from the shadows. Violators were slaughtered on the spot.

The Host: "Enjoy the show."

"Help me—!" A young man nearby screamed, breaking the silence rule. In an instant, his upper body was severed from his waist, collapsing at my feet. A spray of warm, metallic blood drenched my clothes.

My mind went completely numb. The stench of iron filled the air.

Suddenly, the creature turned toward me. "Photography is strictly prohibited inside the venue," it hissed, its distorted face inching closer.

What will you do?
[[Stand your ground, too terrified to move]]
[[Immediately scramble back a few steps]]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 2 [en Scene1.2] {"position":"350,300","size":"100,100"}
All in a sudden, the homeless man grabbed my hand with huge strength, stared at me looking hopeless and panic. He whispered in a spooky tone, |shake>["They’re coming… no one can escape…not even a single one..."]

(link: "Talk to him")
[(set: $drifterHint to true)(set: $friendMurder to false)(go-to: "Response")]
(link: "Push him out of my way")
[(set: $drifterHint to false)(set: $friendMurder to true)(go-to: "Chase away")]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 4 [en Scene1.5] {"position":"600,300","size":"100,100"}
Someone startling me with (text-style:"blink")[a pat on the shoulder suddenly.]

"Whoa! You scared me! Samuel."

Yes, that's my college friend, Samuel. We've been through a lot together. 

"What are you doing here?"

"I’ve seen a lot of people visiting this place recently. ''My friend told me that the circus show is the most brilliant one he had ever seen.'' Therefore, I am here to watch it. And you?
This park has become so popular lately; of course, I had to ride the(that?) wave of popularity. That I've heard some visitors are completely obsessed, going three or four times a week—that seems exaggerated."

"Three or four times? Who goes to the same park multiple times? Crazy!"

"By the way, who was that person earlier?"
(link: "Tell Samuel the truth")[(set: $isHonestAboutDrifter to true)(go-to: "SamuelTalks")]
(link: "Just a weirdo")[(set: $isHonestAboutDrifter to false)(go-to: "SamuelTalks")]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 5 [en Scene1.6] {"position":"725,300","size":"100,100"}
The queue was long. It took us nearly twenty minutes to finally reach the entrance. There, the staff stood with identical, mechanical smiles plastered across their faces. Their professionalism was admirable, yet there was an eerie perfection to it—something I couldn't quite place.

"Welcome to the park. Have a pleasant day," the man in front of us said, his voice as hollow as a recording.

He handed each of us a brochure. I flipped through it, but it was just a collection of mundane safety rules. On the surface, it seemed utterly unremarkable.

[[Next->page 6]]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 6 [en Scene1.6] {"position":"850,300","size":"100,100"}
We arrived at the main gate of the circus and joined the queue. The tent was a striking shade of crimson; with the upbeat music and the constant hum of chatter, the place felt lively—on the surface, at least.

"Welcome."

Please adhere to the following rules:
0. Photography and phone calls are strictly prohibited inside.
0. While waiting, do not shout or chat; do not disturb the performers.
0. When the host prompts the audience, you must respond with thunderous applause.
0. In case of an emergency, remain calm and follow our directions. Do not leave the premises on your own.

Violators will be dealt with by the staff.

I stared at that final line, a sudden shiver involuntary rippling through my body.

Dealt with. What kind of place uses a word like that?

It was all too bizarre. First that terrified drifter, and now this unsettling atmosphere. My suspicious nature began to kick in. I haven’t stumbled into a horror novel, have I?

Samuel noticed my hesitation and tried to comfort me. "Are you okay? You’ve been acting strange since we got here."

What will you do?
[[Pretend everything is fine]]
[[Tell him about the strange atmosphere]]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 8 [en Scene2] {"position":"1100,300","size":"100,100"}
We slipped into our seats, the tent buzzing with anticipation.

Though the rules clearly forbade filming, I couldn’t resist. I slid my camera into a barely noticeable spot, its lens peeking out just enough. Truth be told, no one seemed to care—plenty of visitors were snapping photos, chatting loudly, breaking every rule printed in that brochure.

The lights dimmed. A sudden burst of music filled the air, and the host’s voice thundered across the stage, pulling the atmosphere taut like a drumskin.

“Ladies and gentlemen, welcome to the most spectacular show in the land…”

His words rolled with theatrical grandeur, each syllable designed to electrify the crowd.

“And now, let’s give a big round of applause to our performers today!”

The audience erupted, clapping and cheering with a feverish energy.

[[Next->page 9]]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 9 [en Scene2.1] {"position":"1225,300","size":"100,100"}
The show began as a clown clad in a vibrant costume stepped onto the stage, juggling colorful balls with effortless skill. His routine was fluid, cleverly punctuated by deliberate mishaps that had the children shrieking with laughter.

Next, the beast tamer appeared with a pride of large felines—lions, by the look of them, boasting golden coats and formidable builds. At the crack of a whip or a simple command, they executed a series of stunts: leaping through iron hoops, diving through rings of fire, and balancing on their hind legs.

The crowd erupted in thunderous applause, the energy inside the tent soaring to a fever pitch. Just like that, the two-hour spectacle drew toward its conclusion.

[[Next->page 10]]
(display:"Styles")


:: StoryScript [script]
window.updateSanityBar = function(value) {
  var numericValue = parseInt(String(value).replace(/[^0-9]/g, '')) || 0;
  var bar = document.getElementById('sanity-fill');
  var container = document.getElementById('sanity-container'); // 取得容器
  
  if (bar) {
    bar.style.width = numericValue + '%';
    
    if (numericValue <= 30) {
      bar.style.backgroundColor = '#d4183d';
      if (container) container.classList.add('is-danger');
    } else {
      bar.style.backgroundColor = '#ffffff';
      if (container) container.classList.remove('is-danger');
    }
  }
};

//var audio = document.createElement('audio');
//audio.src = 'https://cdn.freesound.org/previews/511/511496_9405724-lq.mp3';
//audio.play();
//audio.loop = true;


:: StoryStylesheet [stylesheet]
/* Importing fonts from Google Fonts and CDN */
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Alike+Angular&family=Bebas+Neue&family=Work+Sans:ital,wght@0,100..900;1,100..900&display=swap');
@import url('https://fonts.cdnfonts.com/css/walktrought');
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Kaisei+HarunoUmi&family=Shippori+Mincho&display=swap');

/* Default font styling for body and Twine story content */
body, tw-story {
  font-family: "Alike Angular", serif;
  font-weight: 400;
}

/* Hide Twine icons */
tw-icon, tw-include[type="startup"] {
  display: none;
} 

/* Hide the Accessibility blue outline*/
.enchantment-clickblock > :not(tw-enchantment)::after {
  box-shadow: none;
}

/* Add left padding to main story content */
tw-story {
  padding-left: 37%;
}

/* Sidebar styling for Twine interface */
tw-sidebar {
  position: fixed;          /* Sidebar stays fixed on screen */
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 20%;               /* Sidebar takes up 20% of screen width */
  height: 100vh;            /* Full viewport height */
  padding: 2em;
  font-family: "Work Sans", sans-serif;
  font-size: 0.7em;
  color: #888;              /* Light gray text */
  text-align: left;
  display: flex;            /* Flexbox layout for vertical stacking */
  flex-direction: column;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  background: #000;         /* Black background */
}

/* Styling for "healthy" status text */
span.healthy {
  color: #fff;              /* White text */
  font-family:"Bebas Neue", sans-serif;
}

/* Styling for "danger" status text */
span.danger {
  color: #d4183d;               /* Red text for warnings */
  font-family:"Walktrought", serif;
}

/* Background bar for sanity meter */
.sanity-bar-bg {
  width: 100%;
  height: 3px;
  background: #333;         /* Dark gray background */
  border-radius: 2px;
  margin-top: 0em; 
  margin-bottom: 1em;
}

/* Fill bar for sanity meter (dynamic width) */
.sanity-bar-fill {
  height: 100%;
  width: 100%;
  background: #fff;         /* White fill */
  transition: width 0.4s ease; /* Smooth animation when width changes */
}

/* Divider line inside sidebar */
tw-sidebar hr {
  display: block;
  width: 100%;
  height: 1px;
  border: none;
  background-color: #444;   /* Medium gray line */
  margin: 0.8em 0; 
  opacity: 0.5;             /* Slight transparency */
}

/* Push last child element in sidebar to bottom */
tw-sidebar > :last-child {
  margin-top: auto;
  padding-top: 2em;
}

/* BG */
tw-story[tags~="Scene1"] {
  background-image: url("https://i.imgur.com/B5LeAg1.png");
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  background-position: right center;
}

